<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="generative-ui-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>Use AI tools (v0, Claude Artifacts, Galileo, Uizard, Relume) to generate UI layout variants from spec. Generative UI accelerates ideation; requires human refinement. Claude Artifacts is agent-native.</summary>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>generative</tag>
      <tag>ui</tag>
      <tag>design</tag>
      <tag>ai</tag>
      <tag>prototyping</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Generative UI Design</title>

    <summary>Use AI tools (Galileo, Uizard, v0, Claude Artifacts, Relume) to generate multiple UI layout variants from a feature brief, then have a human select and refine. Generative UI accelerates ideation and rapid prototyping; it does not produce production-ready output. Claude Artifacts is the only agent-native path — the agent generates the artifact inline, the human reviews it, and the agent iterates based on feedback.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Manual UI creation is slow for early ideation when the team is undecided on layout patterns. Generating 3–5 variants simultaneously compresses the decision cycle. The key constraint: no tool produces accessible markup, correct component library usage, or brand-compliant output by default — human refinement is always required before production.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Rapid ideation: generating 5–10 UI layout variants from a feature brief before any human design work starts</item>
        <item>Converting a written product spec into interactive prototypes for early stakeholder feedback</item>
        <item>Producing low-fidelity wireframe candidates that a designer then refines</item>
        <item>Generating alternative component implementations (card, list, grid) when the team is undecided</item>
        <item>Bootstrapping a new screen when design system tokens are already defined</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Final, production-ready UI is expected — generative output requires significant designer refinement</item>
        <item>Strict brand compliance is mandatory from the first iteration — AI tools ignore brand guidelines unless explicitly constrained</item>
        <item>Component must integrate with an existing codebase — generated code often uses different component libraries</item>
        <item>WCAG AA/AAA accessibility is non-negotiable from day one — generated UIs consistently miss aria attributes and focus management</item>
        <item>The client or legal team cannot review IP of AI-generated design artifacts</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="tool-comparison">
      <p>Five major generative UI tools with different agent-accessibility profiles.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Galileo — UI generation, production-ready visual quality, no public API (UI-only)</item>
        <item>Uizard — wireframe-to-design rapid prototypes, project API in beta</item>
        <item>v0 (Vercel) — React + Tailwind + shadcn/ui code output, CLI available</item>
        <item>Claude Artifacts — interactive prototypes, most agent-native path</item>
        <item>Relume — wireframe generation from sitemap, Figma-compatible export</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="workflow-stages">
      <p>Five-stage process for integrating generative UI into a product workflow.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Ideation — AI generates 3–5 layout variants from a written spec</item>
        <item>Selection — human curates best variant based on design goals</item>
        <item>Refinement — agent + human iterate on the selected variant</item>
        <item>Brand alignment — human verifies against brand guidelines</item>
        <item>Implementation — AI-assisted coding with accessibility audit before handoff</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="quality-rules">
      <p>Non-negotiable practices for sustainable generative UI workflows.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Generate 3–5 variants per screen, not 1 — comparison is faster than iteration from a single bad start.</statement>
        <rationale>AI-generated layouts are often visually generic. Comparing multiple variants simultaneously exposes the design space faster than iterating on one output.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always start with a written spec before prompting; vague prompts produce generic output.</statement>
        <rationale>"Generate a dashboard" produces unusable output. "Generate a SaaS analytics dashboard with date-range filter, KPI cards, and a line chart" produces useful starting points.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run axe-cli on any generated prototype before stakeholder review.</statement>
        <rationale>No generative UI tool produces accessible keyboard navigation, skip-to-content, or screen-reader-friendly markup by default. Presenting inaccessible UIs as viable designs creates false expectations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat generated code as a sketch, not a PR — always refactor before merging into a real codebase.</statement>
        <rationale>Generated component names often conflict with existing project components. Generated code references props or methods that may not exist in the actual library version the project uses.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Structured prompt for v0 generation">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Generate a UI for: SaaS Analytics Dashboard

User goal: Monitor daily KPIs at a glance
Key actions: filter by date range, compare metrics, export report
Constraints:
- Use Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui components
- Mobile-first, max width 768px
- No placeholder lorem ipsum — use realistic content
- Must include: date-range picker, KPI cards (min 4), chart visualization

Output a complete React component. No external imports beyond shadcn/ui and lucide-react.
]]></code>
        <note>Specific, constraint-based prompts produce usable starting points. Vague prompts produce generic, unusable output.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-native-path">
      <p>Claude Artifacts is the only fully agent-native generative UI surface.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Claude Artifacts for agent-loop iteration — it is the only tool where the agent can see and modify output without a human browser session.</statement>
        <rationale>Galileo has no public API and exports require a human in a Figma plugin. v0 API is not GA as of 2026. Claude Artifacts is generated inline in the agent response and immediately visible to both agent and human.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Document why a variant was rejected — this becomes the signal for better next prompts.</statement>
        <rationale>Non-deterministic output means the same prompt may yield structurally different results across runs. Rejection reasons make prompt improvements systematic rather than trial-and-error.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Iterative refinement pattern in Claude Artifacts">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Previous variant: [paste component code]

Changes requested:
1. Move the CTA button above the fold
2. Replace the card grid with a list view
3. Add a loading skeleton state

Return the updated component only.
]]></code>
        <note>Agent and human iterate within the same artifact. Each iteration is documented, creating a decision trail.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Treating v0 output as production-ready">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# DO NOT DO THIS
v0 generate "create a dashboard" --format react > dashboard.tsx
git add dashboard.tsx
git commit -m "feat: add dashboard"
git push origin main
]]></code>
        <note>v0 output is prototype-grade and requires refactoring, accessibility audit, and component library alignment before any production use.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-anti-patterns">
      <p>Common failure modes when integrating generative UI into product workflows.</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generated layouts are often visually safe/generic.</description>
        <reason>AI tools optimize for "looks like a UI" rather than solving the specific design problem. Color and typography decisions are shallow; no understanding of visual hierarchy principles beyond surface patterns.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generated React/HTML code rarely matches the project's actual component library.</description>
        <reason>Galileo and Uizard outputs are not directly Figma-compatible; import requires manual layer cleanup. v0 generates Tailwind + shadcn/ui exclusively — breaks if the project uses a different stack.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Claude Artifacts previews are sandboxed and cannot test real APIs.</description>
        <reason>Claude Artifacts previews have no persistent state and cannot connect to real APIs in the preview. No fetch(), no localStorage, no external assets. Generated code using these will appear broken in preview.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Relying on reproducibility of generative tools.</description>
        <reason>The same prompt across two runs may yield structurally different components. Do not treat any single generative output as a canonical reference.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using v0 output when the project does not use Tailwind + shadcn/ui.</description>
        <reason>v0 generates Tailwind + shadcn/ui exclusively. If the project uses a different stack, the generated code requires full rewrite of component imports and styling.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Auto-deploying generated UI code to production without designer and developer review.</description>
        <reason>Generated code is prototype-grade. It consistently misses accessibility requirements, may conflict with existing component naming, and uses non-deterministic output that cannot be relied upon for production.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <p>Models hallucinate component APIs: generated code may reference props or methods that do not exist in the actual library version the project uses.</p>
      <p>Generated component names often conflict with existing project components (e.g., `Button`, `Card`) — always namespace or rename before integration.</p>
      <p>Galileo exports to Figma via a plugin that requires a human to manually trigger — no agent path exists.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Always start with a written spec before prompting — "generate a dashboard" produces garbage; "generate a SaaS analytics dashboard with date-range filter, KPI cards, and a line chart component" produces useful starting points</item>
        <item>Generate 3–5 variants per screen, not 1 — comparison is faster than iteration from a single bad start</item>
        <item>Use Claude Artifacts for agent-loop iteration: it is the only tool where the agent can see and modify the output without a human browser session</item>
        <item>Impose component constraints explicitly in every prompt: library, responsive breakpoints, realistic content, no Lorem Ipsum</item>
        <item>Document why a variant was rejected — this becomes the training signal for better next prompts</item>
        <item>Run axe-cli on any generated prototype before a stakeholder review to prevent presenting inaccessible UIs as viable designs</item>
        <item>Treat generated code as a sketch, not a PR — always refactor before merging into a real codebase</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-tools">
      <p>Generative UI services and their agent accessibility profiles.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Claude Artifacts (SaaS) — most agent-native; agent generates artifact inline, no separate API call needed</item>
        <item>v0 by Vercel (SaaS) — CLI available; API in beta as of 2026; outputs Tailwind + shadcn/ui only</item>
        <item>Galileo AI (SaaS) — UI-only; no public API; Figma plugin for export</item>
        <item>Uizard (SaaS) — has a project API in beta; main UX is browser-based; best for wireframe-to-mockup</item>
        <item>Relume (SaaS) — no public API; UI-only; generates Figma-compatible wireframes from sitemap prompts</item>
        <item>Builder.io (SaaS) — REST + SDK; can receive AI-generated component specs and render them visually; agent-compatible</item>
        <item>v0 CLI — generate React components from prompts via terminal</item>
        <item>shadcn/ui CLI — scaffold shadcn component library in project</item>
        <item>Playwright — test generated prototypes for basic interaction</item>
        <item>axe-cli — accessibility audit on rendered generated UI</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <p>Structured patterns for generating usable UI output.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Basic UI generation prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Generate a UI for: {feature_name}

User goal: {user_goal}
Key actions: {action_1}, {action_2}, {action_3}
Constraints:
- Use Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui components
- Mobile-first, max width 768px
- No placeholder lorem ipsum — use realistic content
- Must include: {required_elements}

Output a complete React component. No external imports beyond shadcn/ui and lucide-react.
]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Iterative refinement prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Previous variant: [paste component code]

Changes requested:
1. Move the CTA button above the fold
2. Replace the card grid with a list view
3. Add a loading skeleton state

Return the updated component only.
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/ui-generation-prompt.txt" purpose="Structured prompt template for React/Tailwind UI generation"/>
      <template path="templates/gen-ui.sh" purpose="Batch v0 CLI generation script from a prompts file"/>
    </templates>

